Let \[f(x) =
\begin{cases}
2x + 9 &\text{if }x<-2, \\
5-2x&\text{if }x\ge -2.
\end{cases}
\]Find $f(-7).$

solution:
Using the quadratic formula, we find that the roots of the quadratic are $\frac{-3\pm\sqrt{3^2-4(7)(k)}}{14}=\frac{-3\pm\sqrt{9-28k}}{14}$. Since the problem tells us that these roots must equal $\frac{-3\pm i\sqrt{299}}{14}$, we have \begin{align*} \sqrt{9-28k}&=i\sqrt{299}
\\\Rightarrow\qquad 9-28k&=-299
\\\Rightarrow\qquad -28k&=-308
\\\Rightarrow\qquad k&=\boxed{11}.
\end{align*}

This is a finite geometric series with first term $\frac{1}{3}$, common ratio $\frac{1}{3}$ and $6$ terms. Therefore the sum is: $$\frac{\frac{1}{3}\left(1-\frac{1}{3^{6}}\right)}{1-\frac{1}{3}}
=\frac{\frac{3^{6}-1}{3^{7}}}{\frac{2}{3}}
= \frac{3^{6}-1}{2\cdot3^{6}}=\frac{729-1}{2\cdot 729} = \boxed{\frac{364}{729}}.$$
